data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compile and run without issues:

```csharp
Span<nint>  span  = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system each element is 8 bytes (`nint.Size == 8`). On a 32-bit runtime they'd be 4 bytes. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types backed by `System.IntPtr`/`System.UIntPtr`.
